Project 4 - Travel Package Purchase Predictor¶

August 2021

The purpose of this project is to identify customers who are likely to purchase a new Wellness Tourism Package from the "Visit With Us" travel company.

To target these customers, I will use a historical dataset from the "Visit with us" company to evaluate the characteristics of customers which have previously purchased travel packages.

Using this information, I will be able to assist the Marketing team to derive an effective target market group that is likely to purchase a package. This will ensure that their marketing campaign is more successful, and that the ROI for their marketing campaign is higher.

To select the best model, it's essntial that we identify the appropriate measure to quantify and compare model performance.

In this case, a "positive" is a customer who purchased a travel package. A "negative" is a customer who did not purchase a travel package.

False positive - Model predicted they would buy package, and they did not purchase it False negative - Model predicted they would not buy package, and they did purchase it

To ensure that the marketing campaign has the highest ROI we should reduce the number of false positives, as this would mean that we have wasted marketing dollars on marketing to potential customers who did not buy a package. We should ensure that the model is balanced in terms of measures, but will focus mostly on precision as the key determinant. https://towardsdatascience.com/accuracy-recall-precision-f-score-specificity-which-to-optimize-on-867d3f11124

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

  4. There appear to be very strong correlations between the monthly income, designation and type of product that is pitched, for example manager designation has a correlation of +1 with the deluxe product pitch, senior manager has a correlation of +1 with the standard package, AVP is associate diwth super deluxe, and VP designation has a +1 correlation of the king package pitch
  5. AVP and VP have the highest correlation with monthly income

Next, let's look at each variable by the target variable "ProdTaken". From the discussion board: "While ProdTaken is not specifically the new "Wellness Tourism" package, it is still a tourism package (either Basic, Standard, Deluxe, Super Deluxe, or King).

We don't have enough information about how the packages compare to the new "Wellness Tourism" package so we can't say whether buying a specific package over another package is a better indicator for buying the "Wellness Tourism" package.

As a result, I think the best variable to use as the dependent variable is ProdTaken despite it being a little more general than our final objective."

Key takeaways for the marketing team from intial EDA are:¶

  • Variation by package type is seen, therefore to be most effective we should identify which of these packages most closely resembles the wellness package to determine a more efficient marketing strategy

Using the more general target variable of purchasing a package, we know:¶

-Younger ages may be more likely to purchase package

  • A slightly longer pitch time can lead to more purchases, so train salesmen to slow down and make it personal

  • A lower monthly income might lead to purchasing a package, so there is a market for getting a "deal", need to sell the value of the package and perhaps offer discounts when compared to purchasing items idividually

    -The company reaching out to customers proved to be effective for selling packages, so direct marketing is important

  • city tier can be added as a target market variable (still not clear on if this is the city the customer lives in or the city they would like to visit, need clarity from the data owner)

  • increasing followups showed to be successful for selling packages

  • higher preferred property star led to increased purchasing of packages, again this could be leveraged to offer discounts to nicer hotels

  • Given the relationship with the "number of trips" variable, we will most likely want two separating marketing campaigns, one for people who travel very infrequently (1-3 times) and one for people who travel a lot (7+). While the small number of trips is more frequent in our dataset (mode=2), we do see that those who travel a lot purchase packages more often, therefore two individualized campaigns could both show great success.

    -offering packages to foreign countries could be highly successful, given that having a passport greatly incrasese your chance of purchasing a package

Model evaluation criterion¶

The model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a person doesn't purchase a package, and they do purchase a package (false negative).
  2. Predicting a person will purchase a package and they do not purchase a package (false positive).

Which case is more important?¶

  • To get the most value from marketing dollars we want to minimize the number of false positives.

Which metric to optimize?¶

  • We would want precision to be maximized, while considering balance in the other model performance measures as well.
In [105]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [106]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

dtree_estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight={0:0.35,1:0.65},random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2,10), 
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 7, 10, 15],
              'max_leaf_nodes' : [2, 3, 5, 10,15],
              'min_impurity_decrease': [0.0001,0.001,0.01,0.1]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dtree_estimator, parameters, scoring=scorer,n_jobs=-1)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
dtree_estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
dtree_estimator.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Choose the type of classifier. 
abc_tuned = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    #Let's try different max_depth for base_estimator
    "base_estimator":[DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=1),DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2),
                      DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3)],
    "n_estimators": np.arange(10,80,10),
    "learning_rate":np.arange(0.2,1.6,0.2)
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter  combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(abc_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
abc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
abc_tuned.fit(x_train, y_train)

Final Recommendations¶

In order for the marketing team to launch a sucessful campaign to target customers who are likely to puchase a traveling package, they should rely upon the XG boost model.

They should focus on customers:

  • With a passport
  • Single or unmarried
  • Work for a large business
  • They should also increase the number of follow-ups and lengthen the pitch, training salesmen to slow down and make the pitch personal
  • Older customers with an increased monthly income and take a large number of trips should be targeted
